I have supplied a model with and without (sans) warpstone bits, so the ship can be used as something less specific than a Skaven vehicle.





A few mistakes were made in the late 90's that ended the presence of a couple of races in the Warhammer 40k universe. I made this ship for myself, to fill in one of those vacancies.


Fluff:

The Hrud (or Skaven) Warren Ship is the Hrudii battleship and their primary center of habitation and culture. The Warren Ships are similar to Eldar Craftworlds in that they serve as permanent homes, though are far smaller and vastly more numerous. Their technology, which is nearly as advanced as the Eldar, is powered by rare Warpstone that only the Hrud have found in great quantities.

Along with the various other Hrudii ship classes, the Warren Ship inhabits pockets in between the Immaterium and our own dimension into which they have "tunneled", using Warpstone to power their extradimensional drives. This gives the Hrud nearly unequaled latitude of travel in the galaxy, and insulates them from the predations of warp entities that would otherwise be greatly attracted to the concentrations of Warpstone that they use.


Millennia of relatively undisturbed advancement and inter-warren trading has created a civilization of royal city-states, ruled ostensibly as oligarchies. A city-state of this fashion, called a Clan House, will consist of many Warren Ships and hundreds of other warships and auxiliary craft, (though it stands to reason that greater craft, perhaps rivaling Eldar Craftworlds in size, exist in these realms).


Given their empire's existence below the surface of the material galaxy, it's no wonder that they have only accidentally and improperly been codified by Imperial Magos Biologis adepts. However, the Hrud do need material supplies, which necessitates plying the darker regions of the material galaxy for food and ore. These "forages" sometimes bring them into conflict with the various sentient races of the galaxy, not least of which are the Squats.

EDIT: increased diametre of the pegs that connect the rings to one another and the cap piece, and the size of the guide pegs from the innersphere connector to the ring 2 cross beams. tl:dr made it better

No idea how this prints in a single piece, or the supports involved, as it's really meant to be printed in pieces.

The rings and cap are meant to be put together with a bit of luck and a keen eye, I provided no guides. ring 1 (big one) on the inside, ring 2 next, then cap. Don't overthink where they attach.

Once those are assembled, the inner ball attaches to the Ring_2 cross-support piece, with guide pegs to line up a better fit found on the end of the innerball connector arms.

Print doubles of the rings and cap, of course.

NOTE: This prints at around 120mm, which is in scale with my own fleets, so scale it to your liking

This is a mix of Italianmoose's (https://www.thingiverse.com/Italianmoose/about) and Corvus Obscurus's (https://www.thingiverse.com/Corvus_Obscurus/about) eldar cruisers, to create a simple to assemble Void Stalker. The hull is a mishmash of Italianmoose's cruiser, while the wings are from Corvus's light cruiser.

This is modeled at about 80% of what *I* think the size should be. Although I can't tell how big the original was because I don't have one, this model gets close I'm guessing.

The upper and lower wings are halves, print two of each file. They are identical on each half as well as the left/right wing, so gluing them together for filament prints won't be hard. They fit on the model at a right-angel block, so again, easy assembly.

A Hiveship. I hope you like it, it's different from many out there. I am trying to skip the "extra tyranid claws glued together" look.

The fins are coded front to back by the number of knocks in them, 4 being the front, 3 mid, and 2 rear. They don;t have ball joints, but rather flat surfaces to glue, so feel free to model around that design limitation.

NOTE: This guy is very fat. If you want to bring it more in line with an imperial battleship, I suggest reducing the body by 75%, then stretching out the X axis to 115mm long. This will cause a tad of distort in the valves/spiracles and the fin mounts

Something I hobbled together in TinkerCad.

If you're going to print the sections of the dome separately, good luck lining them up, I believe in you. 

If you want to print the whole top dome as one piece, a setting that connects overhangs at various angles helps. I set mine to 45˚ (in the 'experimental' section of Cura 4.0), and as those overhangs are typically on the underside of a model, it doesn't detract too much from the look. (be aware that those settings on the lower half of the model will then have its "top" flat areas angled up at 45˚, such as the deck of the ring shaped structures around the narrowest part of the model.
